    "body_text": [
      {
        "section": "title",
        "text": "Context Engineering with Redis and LangChain"
      },
      {
        "section": "description",
        "text": "In this 1-hour workshop, you’ll learn how to design scalable AI agents by mastering context engineering — the discipline of structuring memory, retrieval, and reasoning workflows so LLMs behave reliably in production. The session explores how Redis and LangChain enable high-performance agent systems through semantic caching, vector search, and intelligent context management."
      },
      {
        "section": "speaker_name",
        "text": "Robert Shelton"
      },
      {
        "section": "speaker_title",
        "text": "Applied AI Engineer - Redis"
      },
      {
        "section": "speaker_bio",
        "text": "Robert is a builder with a background in data science and full stack engineering. As an Applied AI Engineer at Redis, he focuses on bridging the gap between AI research and real-world applications. In open source, he helps maintain the Redis Vector Library and contributes to integrations with LangChain, LlamaIndex, and LangGraph. He has delivered workshops and consulting engagements for multiple Fortune 50 companies and has spoken at conferences including PyData and CodeMash."
      },
      {
        "section": "workshop_overview",
        "text": "Modern AI systems are shifting from prompt engineering to context engineering, where developers program how information flows into an LLM rather than relying on a single prompt. Instead of treating the model as a chatbot, this approach builds structured pipelines that assemble instructions, retrieved knowledge, memory, and tool outputs into the context window — turning stateless models into reliable, production-ready agents.\nThis workshop explores how Redis and LangChain enable scalable context architectures by combining vector search, semantic caching, and agent memory into a unified system. Attendees will learn how to design efficient context pipelines that reduce token costs, improve latency, and maintain persistent state across sessions — key capabilities for building real-world AI applications beyond demos.\n1. Foundations of Context Engineering\nMoving beyond prompt engineering into programmable context pipelines\nUnderstanding the context window as working memory for agents\nStrategies for selecting, compressing, and isolating context signals\n2. Memory Architectures for AI Agents\nShort-term vs long-term memory design\nRetrieval-augmented generation (RAG) patterns\nUsing Redis vector search and agent memory systems for persistent context\n3. High-Performance Context Pipelines\nSemantic caching to reduce token usage and latency\nContext pruning and summarization strategies\nDesigning for throughput, reliability, and real-time agent interactions\n4. Orchestrating Context with LangChain\nBuilding multi-step agent workflows\nManaging tool outputs, conversation history, and state\nStructuring context flows for scalable production deployments"
      },
      {
        "section": "time_and_location",
        "text": "March 31, 2026\n10:30am - 11:30am\nCobb Galleria"
      },
      {
        "section": "who_should_attend",
        "text": "AI practitioners and researchers."
      },
      {
        "section": "who_should_attend",
        "text": "Developers seeking to transition into advanced agent-building roles."
      },
      {
        "section": "who_should_attend",
        "text": "Organizations looking to implement custom AI solutions."
      }
    ],
